        "correctAnswer": "\\(D_{\\mathbf{v}}f(1,1) = \\langle 2, -2 \\rangle \\cdot \\langle 1, 2 \\rangle = -2\\)",
        "explanationParts": [
          "To compute the directional derivative, we use the formula: \\(D_{\\mathbf{v}}f = \\nabla f \\cdot \\hat{\\mathbf{v}}\\).",
          "First, compute the gradient: \\(\\nabla f(x, y) = \\langle f_x, f_y \\rangle = \\langle 2x, -2y \\rangle\\).",
          "At \\((1, 1)\\), we have \\(\\nabla f(1,1) = \\langle 2, -2 \\rangle\\).",
          "Next, normalize the direction vector \\(\\mathbf{v} = \\langle 1, 2 \\rangle\\):",
          "Magnitude: \\(\\sqrt{1^2 + 2^2} = \\sqrt{5}\\), so \\(\\hat{\\mathbf{v}} = \\left\\langle \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{5}}, \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{5}} \\right\\rangle\\).",
          "Then: \\(D_{\\hat{\\mathbf{v}}}f = \\langle 2, -2 \\rangle \\cdot \\left\\langle \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{5}}, \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{5}} \\right\\rangle = \\frac{2 - 4}{\\sqrt{5}} = -\\frac{2}{\\sqrt{5}}\\).",
          "However, the options refer to the **unnormalized** form, so we compute:",
          "\\(\\langle 2, -2 \\rangle \\cdot \\langle 1, 2 \\rangle = 2(1) + (-2)(2) = 2 - 4 = -2\\).",
          "Therefore, \\(D_{\\mathbf{v}}f(1,1) = -2\\)."
        ],
